Kenya Lionesses begin their quest to qualify for the Rugby Sevens World Cup with tricky tie against Madagascar today in Tunis, Tunisia.The match, which will kickoff at 12:44pm, will be followed by another against Senegal at 2:42 pm before the Kenyan girls wind up their preliminary assignments at 4:40pm, when they face Zimbabwe. For the first time in the women&acirc;&#128;&#153;s competition, the teams will be ranked after the opening day paving way for the quarter finals on SundayThe winner of the of the tournament will represent Africa at the World Rugby Sevens World Cup at the AT&amp;T Stadium in San Francisco on July 20-22 next year. The runners-up also has a chance of qualifying for the Commonwealth Games set for Australia in April next year.The Lionesses have steadily improved and were losing finalists to South Africa last year in the Africa Cup Sevens in Harare losing 22-17 in an epic final .Head coach Kevin Wambua said the girls&acirc;&#128;&#153; mental resilience will be key in the two days of competition.&acirc;&#128;&#156;We will take one game at a time we need to start well and gain some momentum for the second day of action and the girls are relishing the challenge of facing the best the continent has to offer,&acirc;&#128;&#157; said Wambua adding that the ultimate goal is to qualify for the World Cup in San Fransisco. &acirc;&#128;&#156;We know we have to win the African Cup Sevens if we want to play in the World Cup, that&acirc;&#128;&#153;s why this is a big test for us. Our chances of winning it are as good as anyone else&acirc;&#128;&#153;s. The mood in camp right now is very healthy and everyone wants to put their best foot forward and represent Kenya with pride, win the Africa Cup and qualify for the World Cup. That&acirc;&#128;&#153;s our goal.&acirc;&#128;&#157; He added: &acirc;&#128;&#156;I believe we are very capable of qualifying. If you look at last year&acirc;&#128;&#153;s Africa Cup it&acirc;&#128;&#153;s just a matter of belief and decision making which let us down. This time round we have put in all our efforts into training, hard work, mental preparations and making sure we take every game as a final.&acirc;&#128;&#157;Key players for the Lionesses include Doreen Remour, Janet Okello, skipper Philadelphia Olando and Janet Owino.Today&acirc;&#128;&#153;s fixturesSouth Africa v Morocco (10), Uganda v Tunisia (10.22), Kenya v Madagascar (10.44), Zimbabwe v Senegal (11.06), South Africa v Tunisia (11.58), Uganda v Morocco (12.20), Kenya v Senegal (12.42), Zimbabwe v Madagascar (1.04), South Africa v Uganda (1.56), Tunisia v Morocco (2.18), Kenya v Zimbabwe (2.40), Senegal v Madagascar (3.02).